WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.984 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.984 --> 00:00:04.464 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.464 --> 00:00:05.952 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.952 --> 00:00:09.740 align:middle line:90%


00:00:09.740 --> 00:00:12.540 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: So next, we will--

00:00:12.540 --> 00:00:15.660 align:middle line:84%
so we're switching away
from metric spaces,

00:00:15.660 --> 00:00:18.660 align:middle line:84%
and we talk about
differentiation.

00:00:18.660 --> 00:00:30.230 align:middle line:84%
So if we have a function
on R, say, and then

00:00:30.230 --> 00:00:51.860 align:middle line:84%
we say that x that f is
differentiable at x0,

00:00:51.860 --> 00:01:11.130 align:middle line:84%
if the limit here f of dx minus
f of x0, divided by x minus x0,

00:01:11.130 --> 00:01:16.440 align:middle line:84%
if this limit here
exists as x goes to x0.

00:01:16.440 --> 00:01:22.420 align:middle line:90%


00:01:22.420 --> 00:01:25.310 align:middle line:84%
This quotient here is usually
called the difference quotient.

00:01:25.310 --> 00:01:32.340 align:middle line:90%


00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:35.460 align:middle line:84%
And it's always, of course,
when you form this difference

00:01:35.460 --> 00:01:38.820 align:middle line:84%
quotient, it's always
assumed, obviously,

00:01:38.820 --> 00:01:43.770 align:middle line:84%
that x is not equal to x0 so
that the denominator makes

00:01:43.770 --> 00:01:44.770 align:middle line:90%
sense.

00:01:44.770 --> 00:01:49.440 align:middle line:84%
So if this limit here, as x
goes to x0, if this exists,

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:53.700 align:middle line:84%
then we say that the function
f is differentiable at x0.

00:01:53.700 --> 00:01:59.170 align:middle line:84%
And the limit is called
the derivative of f at x0.

00:01:59.170 --> 00:02:03.070 align:middle line:90%
And this is how it's denoted.

00:02:03.070 --> 00:02:12.880 align:middle line:84%
So now the simplest
possible example of this

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:17.410 align:middle line:84%
would be that suppose
that you're looking

00:02:17.410 --> 00:02:19.940 align:middle line:90%
at a function that is constant.

00:02:19.940 --> 00:02:32.620 align:middle line:84%
So f is equal to f
for some constant C.

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:35.720 align:middle line:84%
Then if you're looking at
this difference quotient,

00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:45.160 align:middle line:84%
so f of dx minus f of x0 x minus
x0, well, the value at any point

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:46.010 align:middle line:90%
is C--

00:02:46.010 --> 00:02:52.510 align:middle line:84%
so this is C minus C
divided by x minus y, x0--

00:02:52.510 --> 00:02:56.370 align:middle line:84%
and so the denominator is
0, so this whole thing is 0.

00:02:56.370 --> 00:02:58.350 align:middle line:84%
And so of course,
the limit-- this

00:02:58.350 --> 00:03:02.350 align:middle line:84%
is 0 for each x
and also each x0.

00:03:02.350 --> 00:03:05.470 align:middle line:84%
So in particular, of course,
the limit here exists.

00:03:05.470 --> 00:03:09.300 align:middle line:84%
So the limit here of
the difference quotient

00:03:09.300 --> 00:03:20.340 align:middle line:84%
exists, and it's equal
to 0 because it's

00:03:20.340 --> 00:03:24.900 align:middle line:90%
0 for all x for a given x0.

00:03:24.900 --> 00:03:28.600 align:middle line:84%
So that would be the
simplest possible example.

00:03:28.600 --> 00:03:32.250 align:middle line:90%
The second simplest example.

00:03:32.250 --> 00:03:35.430 align:middle line:84%
Second most simple example
would be that you're

00:03:35.430 --> 00:03:37.060 align:middle line:90%
looking at a linear function.

00:03:37.060 --> 00:03:42.690 align:middle line:84%
So let's say that f
of x is equal to x.

00:03:42.690 --> 00:03:47.765 align:middle line:84%
In this case, the
difference quotient here--

00:03:47.765 --> 00:03:52.830 align:middle line:90%


00:03:52.830 --> 00:03:55.810 align:middle line:90%
well, this here is x.

00:03:55.810 --> 00:03:57.343 align:middle line:90%
This here is x0.

00:03:57.343 --> 00:04:00.490 align:middle line:90%


00:04:00.490 --> 00:04:03.800 align:middle line:84%
So this here is
for each x and x0.

00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:05.030 align:middle line:90%
This is 1.

00:04:05.030 --> 00:04:08.025 align:middle line:84%
So the limit of course,
in this case, also exists.

00:04:08.025 --> 00:04:13.300 align:middle line:90%


00:04:13.300 --> 00:04:17.595 align:middle line:84%
The limit here exists,
and it's equal to 1.

00:04:17.595 --> 00:04:22.780 align:middle line:90%


00:04:22.780 --> 00:04:35.140 align:middle line:84%
And so in this case, f is
differentiable at all points.

00:04:35.140 --> 00:04:39.500 align:middle line:84%
And the derivative at
all points is equal to 0.

00:04:39.500 --> 00:04:43.280 align:middle line:84%
In this case, f here
is also differentiable.

00:04:43.280 --> 00:04:48.400 align:middle line:90%


00:04:48.400 --> 00:04:52.660 align:middle line:84%
And the derivative at
all points is equal to 1.

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:55.640 align:middle line:90%


00:04:55.640 --> 00:04:59.690 align:middle line:84%
So now, in general, how
do we compute the-- so

00:04:59.690 --> 00:05:02.335 align:middle line:84%
how do we compute the
derivative of a function?

00:05:02.335 --> 00:05:10.490 align:middle line:90%


00:05:10.490 --> 00:05:17.580 align:middle line:84%
How do we compute
the derivative?

00:05:17.580 --> 00:05:26.390 align:middle line:90%


00:05:26.390 --> 00:05:30.530 align:middle line:84%
And for that, there
are some basic laws--

00:05:30.530 --> 00:05:31.830 align:middle line:90%
how to compute it.

00:05:31.830 --> 00:05:33.280 align:middle line:90%
So there's these laws--

00:05:33.280 --> 00:05:38.270 align:middle line:90%


00:05:38.270 --> 00:05:45.860 align:middle line:84%
the sum rule, what's
usually called

00:05:45.860 --> 00:06:02.040 align:middle line:84%
the Leibniz rule, the
quotient rule, and then

00:06:02.040 --> 00:06:03.395 align:middle line:90%
also the chain rule.

00:06:03.395 --> 00:06:09.810 align:middle line:90%


00:06:09.810 --> 00:06:17.880 align:middle line:84%
Now let me look at the
first three rules first.

00:06:17.880 --> 00:06:26.640 align:middle line:84%
So I have two
functions, f and g.

00:06:26.640 --> 00:06:29.220 align:middle line:84%
They are defined,
say, on R, but it

00:06:29.220 --> 00:06:35.130 align:middle line:84%
could have been a subset
of R. And I'm assuming

00:06:35.130 --> 00:06:39.975 align:middle line:90%
that they are both and both--

00:06:39.975 --> 00:06:42.760 align:middle line:90%


00:06:42.760 --> 00:06:44.320 align:middle line:90%
actually, we'll need one.

00:06:44.320 --> 00:07:02.410 align:middle line:84%
So both f and g are
differentiable at x0.

00:07:02.410 --> 00:07:04.670 align:middle line:90%
Then we have the following.

00:07:04.670 --> 00:07:05.985 align:middle line:90%
So we have the following lemma.

00:07:05.985 --> 00:07:26.020 align:middle line:90%


00:07:26.020 --> 00:07:28.250 align:middle line:90%
One is we have that--

00:07:28.250 --> 00:07:30.600 align:middle line:84%
so 1, and this is
really the sum rule.

00:07:30.600 --> 00:07:36.160 align:middle line:90%


00:07:36.160 --> 00:07:39.520 align:middle line:84%
We have that the
sum here f plus g--

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:42.400 align:middle line:84%
so the sum of these
two functions, this

00:07:42.400 --> 00:07:45.710 align:middle line:84%
is the function
that is just in x.

00:07:45.710 --> 00:07:50.600 align:middle line:84%
It's just the sum of f
of x and g of x We have

00:07:50.600 --> 00:08:04.670 align:middle line:84%
that this function here, f plus
g, is differentiable at x0.

00:08:04.670 --> 00:08:11.900 align:middle line:84%
And the derivative, f plus g,
the derivative of this at x0

00:08:11.900 --> 00:08:14.160 align:middle line:84%
is just the sum
of the derivative.

00:08:14.160 --> 00:08:27.590 align:middle line:90%


00:08:27.590 --> 00:08:31.615 align:middle line:84%
Let me prove this
one here, by the way.

00:08:31.615 --> 00:08:35.630 align:middle line:90%


00:08:35.630 --> 00:08:36.699 align:middle line:90%
So let's prove this.

00:08:36.699 --> 00:08:42.169 align:middle line:90%


00:08:42.169 --> 00:08:44.130 align:middle line:90%
So we have the sum--

00:08:44.130 --> 00:08:49.690 align:middle line:84%
so we are going to look at--
so we formed the difference

00:08:49.690 --> 00:09:13.070 align:middle line:84%
quotient, so f plus g at x
minus f plus g at x0 x minus x0.

00:09:13.070 --> 00:09:14.780 align:middle line:90%
So now what is this?

00:09:14.780 --> 00:09:27.040 align:middle line:84%
So this is just f of x plus
g of x minus and then f of x0

00:09:27.040 --> 00:09:35.380 align:middle line:84%
plus g of x0, and then
divided by x minus x0.

00:09:35.380 --> 00:09:38.950 align:middle line:84%
And so then you can
split this up into two.

00:09:38.950 --> 00:09:41.680 align:middle line:84%
You can write this
difference quotient

00:09:41.680 --> 00:09:44.240 align:middle line:84%
as if you split it
up if you collect

00:09:44.240 --> 00:09:47.390 align:middle line:90%
the f's in the numerator.

00:09:47.390 --> 00:09:49.330 align:middle line:90%
So I just collect the f's.

00:09:49.330 --> 00:09:53.180 align:middle line:90%


00:09:53.180 --> 00:09:57.290 align:middle line:84%
And then, afterwards, I collect
and I put it on two different

00:09:57.290 --> 00:10:02.530 align:middle line:84%
fractions, separate them out,
and then I collect the g's.

00:10:02.530 --> 00:10:13.100 align:middle line:90%


00:10:13.100 --> 00:10:18.120 align:middle line:84%
And now you see that because
f is differentiable at x0,

00:10:18.120 --> 00:10:23.730 align:middle line:84%
this thing here, as x goes to
x0, this here goes to f prime.

00:10:23.730 --> 00:10:28.380 align:middle line:84%
So this here goes
to f prime of x0.

00:10:28.380 --> 00:10:30.870 align:middle line:84%
This is what this
difference quotient here.

00:10:30.870 --> 00:10:34.970 align:middle line:84%
And this difference quotient
goes to g prime of 0.

00:10:34.970 --> 00:10:38.400 align:middle line:84%
So you have that indeed,
it does converge.

00:10:38.400 --> 00:10:40.980 align:middle line:84%
And this is what
it converges to.

00:10:40.980 --> 00:10:44.370 align:middle line:84%
And so this proves that the
sum of these two functions

00:10:44.370 --> 00:10:47.280 align:middle line:84%
is also differentiable,
and their derivative

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:49.000 align:middle line:90%
is the sum of the derivative.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:52.480 align:middle line:84%
The next thing we will
prove is Leibniz rule.

00:10:52.480 --> 00:10:59.460 align:middle line:84%
But before that, I need to
step back and I want to--

00:10:59.460 --> 00:11:03.240 align:middle line:84%
so maybe I'll just state
it and then we'll go back

00:11:03.240 --> 00:11:04.780 align:middle line:90%
and we need something.

00:11:04.780 --> 00:11:06.700 align:middle line:84%
The next is what's
called Leibniz rule.

00:11:06.700 --> 00:11:11.460 align:middle line:90%


00:11:11.460 --> 00:11:14.140 align:middle line:84%
So you could also call
it a product rule,

00:11:14.140 --> 00:11:18.360 align:middle line:84%
but it's really quite generally
called the Leibniz rule.

00:11:18.360 --> 00:11:21.150 align:middle line:84%
And so this is
when you're looking

00:11:21.150 --> 00:11:23.200 align:middle line:84%
at the products of
these functions.

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:28.500 align:middle line:84%
So the product
function is a function

00:11:28.500 --> 00:11:33.785 align:middle line:84%
in x that is just the
product of f of x and g of x.

00:11:33.785 --> 00:11:41.650 align:middle line:90%


00:11:41.650 --> 00:11:52.320 align:middle line:84%
And Leibniz rule
says the following,

00:11:52.320 --> 00:11:56.500 align:middle line:84%
that if f and g are
differentiable at x0,

00:11:56.500 --> 00:11:58.750 align:middle line:84%
then the product of
these two function

00:11:58.750 --> 00:12:04.060 align:middle line:84%
here is also
differentiable at x0,

00:12:04.060 --> 00:12:06.760 align:middle line:84%
and the derivative
of the product

00:12:06.760 --> 00:12:11.650 align:middle line:84%
is the derivative of the
first function at x0 times

00:12:11.650 --> 00:12:14.920 align:middle line:84%
the value of the
second function at x0

00:12:14.920 --> 00:12:20.600 align:middle line:84%
plus the symmetric
thing in f and g,

00:12:20.600 --> 00:12:28.490 align:middle line:84%
which is the value of f at x0
times the derivative of g at x0.

00:12:28.490 --> 00:12:31.730 align:middle line:84%
So the product is
differentiable at x0 also.

00:12:31.730 --> 00:12:33.950 align:middle line:84%
And this is what
the derivative is.

00:12:33.950 --> 00:12:36.970 align:middle line:84%
And in the notes, I just
copied a little bit of thing

00:12:36.970 --> 00:12:40.040 align:middle line:84%
just for fun from
Wikipedia about Leibniz

00:12:40.040 --> 00:12:41.930 align:middle line:84%
that was kind of an
interesting figure

00:12:41.930 --> 00:12:46.920 align:middle line:84%
and played an important
role a long time ago.

00:12:46.920 --> 00:12:50.840 align:middle line:84%
So before I want to prove
this, let me step back

00:12:50.840 --> 00:12:59.570 align:middle line:84%
and let me make an observation
about what it means to be

00:12:59.570 --> 00:13:01.570 align:middle line:90%
differentiable at a point.

00:13:01.570 --> 00:13:04.280 align:middle line:90%


00:13:04.280 --> 00:13:07.090 align:middle line:90%
So this is the next lemma.

00:13:07.090 --> 00:13:12.560 align:middle line:90%


00:13:12.560 --> 00:13:25.530 align:middle line:84%
So you have a function f on R
into R. And you assume that f--

00:13:25.530 --> 00:13:38.920 align:middle line:84%
so if f here is
differentiable at x0,

00:13:38.920 --> 00:13:52.900 align:middle line:84%
then I claim that then f here
is also continuous at x0.

00:13:52.900 --> 00:13:55.600 align:middle line:90%


00:13:55.600 --> 00:13:58.660 align:middle line:84%
So in other words,
being differentiable

00:13:58.660 --> 00:14:01.630 align:middle line:84%
is stronger than
being continuous.

00:14:01.630 --> 00:14:04.090 align:middle line:84%
In a minute, we will see
an example of something

00:14:04.090 --> 00:14:07.210 align:middle line:84%
that's continuous but
not differentiable.

00:14:07.210 --> 00:14:12.435 align:middle line:84%
And so now let's
try to prove that.

00:14:12.435 --> 00:14:25.490 align:middle line:90%


00:14:25.490 --> 00:14:27.770 align:middle line:84%
So I'm assuming that
it's differentiable.

00:14:27.770 --> 00:14:37.130 align:middle line:84%
So this means that this
difference quotient here

00:14:37.130 --> 00:14:38.220 align:middle line:90%
has a limit.

00:14:38.220 --> 00:14:44.720 align:middle line:84%
And that limit is the
derivative as x goes to x0.

00:14:44.720 --> 00:14:59.750 align:middle line:84%
So this means that there exists
a delta greater than 0 such

00:14:59.750 --> 00:15:11.930 align:middle line:84%
that if x here minus x0
is less than delta y--

00:15:11.930 --> 00:15:17.360 align:middle line:84%
of course, I'm assuming
that it's not equal to 0.

00:15:17.360 --> 00:15:22.910 align:middle line:84%
If it is less than, the
difference between x and x0

00:15:22.910 --> 00:15:26.150 align:middle line:84%
is less than delta,
then this difference

00:15:26.150 --> 00:15:36.060 align:middle line:84%
quotient here, then f of
dx minus f of x here x

00:15:36.060 --> 00:15:42.150 align:middle line:84%
minus x minus x0
minus f prime of x0--

00:15:42.150 --> 00:15:47.050 align:middle line:84%
this thing here have
to be less than 1.

00:15:47.050 --> 00:15:50.700 align:middle line:84%
I mean, this is just using
that this limit exists,

00:15:50.700 --> 00:15:52.620 align:middle line:90%
and I'm using--

00:15:52.620 --> 00:15:55.145 align:middle line:90%
in place of epsilon I'm using 1.

00:15:55.145 --> 00:16:06.330 align:middle line:90%


00:16:06.330 --> 00:16:13.050 align:middle line:84%
Now so this means just
multiplying over and multiplying

00:16:13.050 --> 00:16:13.840 align:middle line:90%
over.

00:16:13.840 --> 00:16:21.600 align:middle line:84%
You get that f of x
minus f of x minus 0

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:30.675 align:middle line:84%
minus f prime of x0,
this thing here--

00:16:30.675 --> 00:16:33.670 align:middle line:90%


00:16:33.670 --> 00:16:47.530 align:middle line:84%
and I'm multiplying both
sides, so multiply both sides

00:16:47.530 --> 00:16:51.890 align:middle line:90%
by x minus x0.

00:16:51.890 --> 00:16:53.800 align:middle line:90%
This is a positive thing.

00:16:53.800 --> 00:16:56.540 align:middle line:84%
So multiplying both
things by that,

00:16:56.540 --> 00:17:01.540 align:middle line:84%
so then I get this
thing here, x minus x0.

00:17:01.540 --> 00:17:06.970 align:middle line:84%
And then I get less or less
strictly less than x minus x0

00:17:06.970 --> 00:17:09.640 align:middle line:84%
because this is
strictly positive

00:17:09.640 --> 00:17:11.770 align:middle line:90%
because x is not equal to x0.

00:17:11.770 --> 00:17:13.480 align:middle line:90%
So I have that.

00:17:13.480 --> 00:17:18.530 align:middle line:84%
And so I get that-- so
now I just split it up

00:17:18.530 --> 00:17:30.620 align:middle line:84%
so I have that f of dx minus
f of x0 is now less than x

00:17:30.620 --> 00:17:41.810 align:middle line:84%
minus x0 plus f prime of x
minus 0 times x minus x0.

00:17:41.810 --> 00:17:45.140 align:middle line:90%


00:17:45.140 --> 00:17:47.810 align:middle line:84%
I mean, this is just
the triangle inequality

00:17:47.810 --> 00:17:54.920 align:middle line:84%
that we've used many
times, just depend on R.

00:17:54.920 --> 00:18:00.080 align:middle line:84%
And so now you see
that if you now--

00:18:00.080 --> 00:18:05.810 align:middle line:90%


00:18:05.810 --> 00:18:09.970 align:middle line:84%
and this here, of course,
I can also write like this.

00:18:09.970 --> 00:18:12.500 align:middle line:90%


00:18:12.500 --> 00:18:14.870 align:middle line:84%
I can just factor
this out, and I

00:18:14.870 --> 00:18:21.600 align:middle line:84%
can write it as 1 plus f
prime of x0 norm, like this.

00:18:21.600 --> 00:18:22.700 align:middle line:90%
That's fine.

00:18:22.700 --> 00:18:25.760 align:middle line:84%
And so now if I want
this thing here--

00:18:25.760 --> 00:18:32.530 align:middle line:84%
so now you want to prove
that f is continuous at x0.

00:18:32.530 --> 00:18:36.630 align:middle line:84%
So you want this here to be
less than some given epsilon.

00:18:36.630 --> 00:18:46.050 align:middle line:84%
So given epsilon
greater than 0, you

00:18:46.050 --> 00:18:54.910 align:middle line:90%
let delta 1 be the minimum of--

00:18:54.910 --> 00:18:59.730 align:middle line:84%
if you set delta 1 to be
the minimum of the delta

00:18:59.730 --> 00:19:04.080 align:middle line:84%
that I already chose, so
then I have this inequality,

00:19:04.080 --> 00:19:17.130 align:middle line:84%
and then epsilon over
1 plus f prime of x0.

00:19:17.130 --> 00:19:28.430 align:middle line:84%
So if I choose delta like this,
then I have this inequality.

00:19:28.430 --> 00:19:30.630 align:middle line:90%
I fill in that.

00:19:30.630 --> 00:19:38.420 align:middle line:84%
So now I'm assuming that this
thing here is less than delta 1.

00:19:38.420 --> 00:19:42.480 align:middle line:84%
So again, I have this inequality
because it's less than delta.

00:19:42.480 --> 00:19:49.160 align:middle line:84%
So then when I fill in
here delta 1 for this,

00:19:49.160 --> 00:19:56.360 align:middle line:84%
then I see that this thing here
times this is less than epsilon.

00:19:56.360 --> 00:20:09.060 align:middle line:84%
You see this holds when x
minus x0 is less than delta 1.

00:20:09.060 --> 00:20:13.650 align:middle line:84%
Again, because if it's less than
delta 1, it's less than delta,

00:20:13.650 --> 00:20:15.510 align:middle line:90%
so I have this inequality.

00:20:15.510 --> 00:20:21.980 align:middle line:84%
And then I can use that delta
1 since this is less than this.

00:20:21.980 --> 00:20:24.310 align:middle line:90%
And then I get this inequality.

00:20:24.310 --> 00:20:28.800 align:middle line:90%


00:20:28.800 --> 00:20:31.840 align:middle line:84%
So this is really
what we want to prove.

00:20:31.840 --> 00:20:34.240 align:middle line:84%
We want to prove that
if it's differentiable,

00:20:34.240 --> 00:20:36.310 align:middle line:90%
then it's also continuous.

00:20:36.310 --> 00:20:39.450 align:middle line:84%
And the continuity
here, I proved it

00:20:39.450 --> 00:20:44.590 align:middle line:84%
with epsilon and delta that
really should prove it.

00:20:44.590 --> 00:20:48.090 align:middle line:90%


00:20:48.090 --> 00:20:50.350 align:middle line:90%
Now let's look at some examples.

00:20:50.350 --> 00:20:55.600 align:middle line:84%
So this means that if a
function is differentiable,

00:20:55.600 --> 00:20:56.906 align:middle line:90%
then it's continuous.

00:20:56.906 --> 00:21:01.830 align:middle line:90%


00:21:01.830 --> 00:21:07.300 align:middle line:84%
Let me give you an example
of a function that is --

00:21:07.300 --> 00:21:12.690 align:middle line:84%
so let me give you
three examples.

00:21:12.690 --> 00:21:18.010 align:middle line:84%
The first example is
maybe the simplest one.

00:21:18.010 --> 00:21:21.030 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
function f of x that

00:21:21.030 --> 00:21:24.470 align:middle line:84%
is equal to the
absolute value of x.

00:21:24.470 --> 00:21:30.970 align:middle line:84%
So f here is
defined on R into R.

00:21:30.970 --> 00:21:33.700 align:middle line:84%
And it's just the
absolute value.

00:21:33.700 --> 00:21:39.140 align:middle line:84%
And so the absolute value
here we've seen before.

00:21:39.140 --> 00:21:42.116 align:middle line:90%
So f here is continuous.

00:21:42.116 --> 00:21:46.630 align:middle line:90%


00:21:46.630 --> 00:21:52.180 align:middle line:84%
It's continuous at all points,
in particular, of course, at 0.

00:21:52.180 --> 00:21:55.340 align:middle line:84%
But if you now form the
difference quotient.

00:21:55.340 --> 00:21:58.880 align:middle line:84%
Suppose that x here
is bigger than 0.

00:21:58.880 --> 00:22:01.700 align:middle line:84%
And now look at the
difference quotient.

00:22:01.700 --> 00:22:03.250 align:middle line:90%
So the difference quotient--

00:22:03.250 --> 00:22:09.700 align:middle line:90%


00:22:09.700 --> 00:22:18.400 align:middle line:84%
quotient at x0 equal
to 0 if you're looking

00:22:18.400 --> 00:22:21.680 align:middle line:90%
at that difference quotient.

00:22:21.680 --> 00:22:24.330 align:middle line:84%
And you first look at
where x is positive.

00:22:24.330 --> 00:22:30.710 align:middle line:84%
If x is positive, then
f of x minus f of 0--

00:22:30.710 --> 00:22:33.440 align:middle line:84%
x minus 0, this
difference quotient here.

00:22:33.440 --> 00:22:37.550 align:middle line:84%
If x is positive, then
this thing here is just x.

00:22:37.550 --> 00:22:41.940 align:middle line:90%
So this is x minus 0, x minus 0.

00:22:41.940 --> 00:22:44.760 align:middle line:90%
So this here is 1.

00:22:44.760 --> 00:22:46.530 align:middle line:90%
This difference quotient is 1.

00:22:46.530 --> 00:22:48.780 align:middle line:90%
This is when x is positive.

00:22:48.780 --> 00:22:55.250 align:middle line:84%
When x is negative,
then f of x--

00:22:55.250 --> 00:23:01.730 align:middle line:84%
if x is negative, then the
absolute value is minus x.

00:23:01.730 --> 00:23:07.820 align:middle line:84%
So the difference quotient
here f of x minus f of 0,

00:23:07.820 --> 00:23:11.150 align:middle line:90%
which is 0, x minus 0--

00:23:11.150 --> 00:23:17.960 align:middle line:84%
this here is just
minus x divided by x.

00:23:17.960 --> 00:23:20.910 align:middle line:90%
But this thing here is minus 1.

00:23:20.910 --> 00:23:29.760 align:middle line:84%
So if you're looking at the
difference quotient that

00:23:29.760 --> 00:23:33.180 align:middle line:84%
comes from looking at
the derivative is 0,

00:23:33.180 --> 00:23:37.920 align:middle line:84%
then when you approach
0 from the right,

00:23:37.920 --> 00:23:40.930 align:middle line:84%
then the difference
quotient is 1.

00:23:40.930 --> 00:23:44.740 align:middle line:90%
When you approach it from the--

00:23:44.740 --> 00:23:46.740 align:middle line:84%
and when you approach
it from the left,

00:23:46.740 --> 00:23:49.360 align:middle line:84%
then the difference
quotient is minus 1.

00:23:49.360 --> 00:23:51.670 align:middle line:90%
So it doesn't have a limit.

00:23:51.670 --> 00:23:54.250 align:middle line:84%
It has a limit from the
right from the left,

00:23:54.250 --> 00:23:57.180 align:middle line:84%
but it doesn't have a
limit if you don't restrict

00:23:57.180 --> 00:23:59.100 align:middle line:90%
where it's coming from.

00:23:59.100 --> 00:24:03.850 align:middle line:84%
So this function here
is not differentiable.

00:24:03.850 --> 00:24:05.580 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:24:05.580 --> 00:24:08.460 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Can you define
what it means when they have

00:24:08.460 --> 00:24:11.090 align:middle line:90%
a function of x [INAUDIBLE]?

00:24:11.090 --> 00:24:22.490 align:middle line:90%


00:24:22.490 --> 00:24:24.730 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: So we did this
earlier in the class.

00:24:24.730 --> 00:24:28.260 align:middle line:90%


00:24:28.260 --> 00:24:34.610 align:middle line:84%
So that's the
difference quotient here

00:24:34.610 --> 00:24:45.380 align:middle line:84%
that this thing here is
converging to some number,

00:24:45.380 --> 00:24:47.330 align:middle line:90%
say a.

00:24:47.330 --> 00:24:53.810 align:middle line:84%
This here means that for
all epsilon greater than 0,

00:24:53.810 --> 00:25:04.280 align:middle line:84%
there exists a delta greater
than 0 such that if x minus x0

00:25:04.280 --> 00:25:10.460 align:middle line:84%
is less than delta and,
again, x is assumed

00:25:10.460 --> 00:25:12.800 align:middle line:90%
to be different from x0.

00:25:12.800 --> 00:25:17.070 align:middle line:84%
If you have that, then
this difference quotient

00:25:17.070 --> 00:25:31.260 align:middle line:84%
here minus this a is supposed
to be less than epsilon.

00:25:31.260 --> 00:25:32.950 align:middle line:90%
And that's this.

00:25:32.950 --> 00:25:37.620 align:middle line:90%


00:25:37.620 --> 00:25:40.740 align:middle line:84%
And so you see,
again, in this example

00:25:40.740 --> 00:25:45.660 align:middle line:84%
that we just looked at, where
in the example that we just

00:25:45.660 --> 00:25:46.260 align:middle line:90%
looked at--

00:25:46.260 --> 00:25:49.440 align:middle line:90%


00:25:49.440 --> 00:25:54.030 align:middle line:84%
so in the example
where f of x was

00:25:54.030 --> 00:26:00.330 align:middle line:84%
equal to the absolute value of
x, then if you were graphing it,

00:26:00.330 --> 00:26:04.200 align:middle line:90%
then this looks like this.

00:26:04.200 --> 00:26:07.590 align:middle line:84%
And we saw that the
difference quotient

00:26:07.590 --> 00:26:11.380 align:middle line:84%
when you approach it over here,
the difference quotient was 1.

00:26:11.380 --> 00:26:14.410 align:middle line:84%
When you approach it over
here, the difference quotient

00:26:14.410 --> 00:26:15.620 align:middle line:90%
is minus 1.

00:26:15.620 --> 00:26:21.100 align:middle line:84%
So if you take a tiny
little interval around 0,

00:26:21.100 --> 00:26:27.740 align:middle line:84%
then the difference quotient
could be either minus 1 or 1.

00:26:27.740 --> 00:26:31.550 align:middle line:84%
But however small you
make this little interval,

00:26:31.550 --> 00:26:36.050 align:middle line:84%
it's not like that it converges
to some number because it has--

00:26:36.050 --> 00:26:37.580 align:middle line:90%
it is both.

00:26:37.580 --> 00:26:42.070 align:middle line:84%
There are both cases where it's
1 and cases where it's minus 1.

00:26:42.070 --> 00:26:44.720 align:middle line:90%


00:26:44.720 --> 00:26:48.280 align:middle line:84%
So that's like
the first example.

00:26:48.280 --> 00:26:52.840 align:middle line:84%
And again, you know of a
function that is continuous,

00:26:52.840 --> 00:26:56.630 align:middle line:84%
but it's not
differentiable at 0.

00:26:56.630 --> 00:27:00.460 align:middle line:90%
In this case, it was a 0.

00:27:00.460 --> 00:27:03.170 align:middle line:84%
And maybe a little bit
more interesting example,

00:27:03.170 --> 00:27:08.120 align:middle line:84%
along the same line,
is the following.

00:27:08.120 --> 00:27:30.920 align:middle line:90%


00:27:30.920 --> 00:27:35.960 align:middle line:84%
So this is, again, a
function on R into R,

00:27:35.960 --> 00:27:42.240 align:middle line:84%
and I set f of x equal to
x times sine of 1 over x.

00:27:42.240 --> 00:27:45.510 align:middle line:84%
This here is not
really defined at 0.

00:27:45.510 --> 00:27:47.850 align:middle line:84%
So I need to define
it also at 0.

00:27:47.850 --> 00:27:54.540 align:middle line:84%
So when x is equal to 0, then
I just set it equal to 0.

00:27:54.540 --> 00:28:02.840 align:middle line:84%
And otherwise, I set it equal
to x times sine of 1 over x.

00:28:02.840 --> 00:28:06.260 align:middle line:84%
And so the thing is that this
function here, so f here,

00:28:06.260 --> 00:28:07.476 align:middle line:90%
is continuous.

00:28:07.476 --> 00:28:12.540 align:middle line:90%


00:28:12.540 --> 00:28:18.160 align:middle line:84%
In particular, it's
continuous at 0.

00:28:18.160 --> 00:28:19.750 align:middle line:84%
It's actually
continuous everywhere,

00:28:19.750 --> 00:28:23.830 align:middle line:84%
but I'm mostly
interested in it at 0.

00:28:23.830 --> 00:28:25.480 align:middle line:90%
The graph of this--

00:28:25.480 --> 00:28:35.730 align:middle line:84%
so remember that sine function
looks like this, That at 0,

00:28:35.730 --> 00:28:41.860 align:middle line:84%
at pi, at 2 pi, at
3 pi, and so on.

00:28:41.860 --> 00:28:45.180 align:middle line:90%
And all of these--

00:28:45.180 --> 00:28:49.870 align:middle line:84%
or at all integer multiples,
also, for the negative ones,

00:28:49.870 --> 00:28:56.910 align:middle line:84%
at all integer multiple of
pi, sine function vanishes.

00:28:56.910 --> 00:29:01.110 align:middle line:84%
And in between here,
it is at pi over 2,

00:29:01.110 --> 00:29:04.540 align:middle line:84%
it achieves its
maximum, which is 1.

00:29:04.540 --> 00:29:08.820 align:middle line:84%
And so the function
looks like this.

00:29:08.820 --> 00:29:09.840 align:middle line:90%
So this here is 1.

00:29:09.840 --> 00:29:13.690 align:middle line:90%


00:29:13.690 --> 00:29:17.230 align:middle line:84%
That's how a sine
function looks like.

00:29:17.230 --> 00:29:20.320 align:middle line:84%
And so now if you're
looking at sine of 1

00:29:20.320 --> 00:29:25.990 align:middle line:84%
over x, that's going to be a
function as you're going down.

00:29:25.990 --> 00:29:28.990 align:middle line:84%
So if you're looking at
this-- here's a sine of x.

00:29:28.990 --> 00:29:34.060 align:middle line:84%
But if you're looking at sine
of 1 over x, as x goes to 0,

00:29:34.060 --> 00:29:36.620 align:middle line:90%
this becomes very large.

00:29:36.620 --> 00:29:39.490 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
as you're going to 0,

00:29:39.490 --> 00:29:45.790 align:middle line:84%
it goes very rapidly
through these periods, where

00:29:45.790 --> 00:29:48.620 align:middle line:84%
it oscillates between
negative 1 and 1.

00:29:48.620 --> 00:29:50.790 align:middle line:90%
So the value here is minus 1.

00:29:50.790 --> 00:29:53.320 align:middle line:90%


00:29:53.320 --> 00:30:04.910 align:middle line:84%
And so it will look like this
that it will again fluctuate.

00:30:04.910 --> 00:30:10.390 align:middle line:84%
It will fluctuate, but it will
fluctuate much more rapidly.

00:30:10.390 --> 00:30:14.173 align:middle line:84%
So if this here,
say, was 1 over pi.

00:30:14.173 --> 00:30:17.370 align:middle line:90%


00:30:17.370 --> 00:30:24.480 align:middle line:84%
And 1 over pi is the same
as pi, there, it would be 0.

00:30:24.480 --> 00:30:26.746 align:middle line:90%
And it would like fluctuate.

00:30:26.746 --> 00:30:30.490 align:middle line:90%


00:30:30.490 --> 00:30:32.350 align:middle line:84%
So it will look like
something like this,

00:30:32.350 --> 00:30:33.700 align:middle line:90%
but it will fluctuate.

00:30:33.700 --> 00:30:36.330 align:middle line:90%


00:30:36.330 --> 00:30:43.350 align:middle line:84%
And then, as you're going away,
it will fluctuate less often.

00:30:43.350 --> 00:30:50.490 align:middle line:84%
So as you're going down towards
0, it will fluctuate a lot.

00:30:50.490 --> 00:30:54.520 align:middle line:84%
Because sine always is
between minus 1 and 1,

00:30:54.520 --> 00:30:58.660 align:middle line:84%
the value here will always
be between minus 1 and 1.

00:30:58.660 --> 00:31:04.300 align:middle line:84%
But as you're going towards 0
from the right or from the left,

00:31:04.300 --> 00:31:07.520 align:middle line:84%
it's going to fluctuate
more and more.

00:31:07.520 --> 00:31:10.915 align:middle line:84%
As you're going away from 0,
it's fluctuating less and less.

00:31:10.915 --> 00:31:14.600 align:middle line:90%


00:31:14.600 --> 00:31:17.640 align:middle line:84%
So this is the function
I'm interested in.

00:31:17.640 --> 00:31:27.950 align:middle line:84%
But when you multiply
through by x, then you see,

00:31:27.950 --> 00:31:31.040 align:middle line:84%
when you multiply through
by x, it's fluctuating,

00:31:31.040 --> 00:31:34.400 align:middle line:84%
but it's always fluctuating
between minus 1 and 1.

00:31:34.400 --> 00:31:41.180 align:middle line:84%
If you multiply it by x,
then as you're going to 0,

00:31:41.180 --> 00:31:48.230 align:middle line:84%
this here will squeeze down, and
the fluctuation will be 0 at 0.

00:31:48.230 --> 00:31:52.580 align:middle line:84%
So it's easy to see that this
function here-- so is indeed

00:31:52.580 --> 00:31:55.070 align:middle line:90%
continuous.

00:31:55.070 --> 00:31:57.390 align:middle line:84%
But let's look at the
difference quotient.

00:31:57.390 --> 00:31:59.160 align:middle line:90%
So the difference quotient--

00:31:59.160 --> 00:32:08.300 align:middle line:90%


00:32:08.300 --> 00:32:12.080 align:middle line:84%
so if we look at the difference
quotient, so we're looking at--

00:32:12.080 --> 00:32:15.170 align:middle line:84%
and we just look at the
difference quotient at 0.

00:32:15.170 --> 00:32:19.490 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
difference quotient.

00:32:19.490 --> 00:32:23.630 align:middle line:90%
And so it's x sine 1 over x.

00:32:23.630 --> 00:32:26.605 align:middle line:84%
The value at 0 by
definition was 0.

00:32:26.605 --> 00:32:30.380 align:middle line:90%


00:32:30.380 --> 00:32:34.250 align:middle line:84%
And so you see
that now this here,

00:32:34.250 --> 00:32:39.980 align:middle line:84%
this here becomes just x
sine 1 over x divided by x.

00:32:39.980 --> 00:32:42.690 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that this
here cancel with that.

00:32:42.690 --> 00:32:45.950 align:middle line:90%
So you just get sine 1 over x.

00:32:45.950 --> 00:32:49.020 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that
now, as x goes to--

00:32:49.020 --> 00:32:53.870 align:middle line:84%
so when x here goes to
0, this here fluctuates.

00:32:53.870 --> 00:33:07.620 align:middle line:84%
This here fluctuates
between minus 1 and 1.

00:33:07.620 --> 00:33:10.020 align:middle line:84%
But it doesn't have
a limit because it's

00:33:10.020 --> 00:33:11.580 align:middle line:90%
fluctuating wider and wider.

00:33:11.580 --> 00:33:16.120 align:middle line:90%
So this is an example again--

00:33:16.120 --> 00:33:21.780 align:middle line:84%
this is another example of a
function that is continuous at 0

00:33:21.780 --> 00:33:23.320 align:middle line:90%
but not differentiable at 0.

00:33:23.320 --> 00:33:25.145 align:middle line:84%
It's actually much
worse than the previous.

00:33:25.145 --> 00:33:30.880 align:middle line:90%


00:33:30.880 --> 00:33:37.290 align:middle line:84%
The previous example that was--
this example is much more tame.

00:33:37.290 --> 00:33:39.790 align:middle line:90%
It is not differentiable at 0.

00:33:39.790 --> 00:33:44.460 align:middle line:84%
But if you were to restrict
to just positive things,

00:33:44.460 --> 00:33:47.380 align:middle line:90%
then it would be differentiable.

00:33:47.380 --> 00:33:50.160 align:middle line:84%
You can also define
derivative-- so,

00:33:50.160 --> 00:33:53.020 align:middle line:84%
in general, when we
define derivative,

00:33:53.020 --> 00:33:56.410 align:middle line:84%
we let it be defined in a
neighborhood of that point,

00:33:56.410 --> 00:33:57.970 align:middle line:90%
so on either side.

00:33:57.970 --> 00:34:00.280 align:middle line:84%
But if you were
considering where you were,

00:34:00.280 --> 00:34:04.450 align:middle line:84%
allowing the function just
to be defined at this point

00:34:04.450 --> 00:34:07.630 align:middle line:84%
and then to the right,
say, or to the left,

00:34:07.630 --> 00:34:10.690 align:middle line:84%
then this function
would be differentiable.

00:34:10.690 --> 00:34:15.639 align:middle line:84%
But in this example
here, it doesn't

00:34:15.639 --> 00:34:19.060 align:middle line:84%
matter if you restrict the
interval to just to the right

00:34:19.060 --> 00:34:19.850 align:middle line:90%
or to the left.

00:34:19.850 --> 00:34:21.280 align:middle line:90%
It's still not differentiable.

00:34:21.280 --> 00:34:26.980 align:middle line:84%
So this says something about
this example, something

00:34:26.980 --> 00:34:32.230 align:middle line:84%
about that it fluctuates
wildly and that is causing it

00:34:32.230 --> 00:34:35.920 align:middle line:90%
not to be differentiable.

00:34:35.920 --> 00:34:40.100 align:middle line:90%
Again, if you defined it--

00:34:40.100 --> 00:34:43.570 align:middle line:84%
if you didn't have this
kind of-- the x here

00:34:43.570 --> 00:34:47.080 align:middle line:84%
is serving as some
of-- it's dampening

00:34:47.080 --> 00:34:49.040 align:middle line:90%
how much it's fluctuating.

00:34:49.040 --> 00:34:54.340 align:middle line:84%
So if there wasn't an x here,
then this function wouldn't-- it

00:34:54.340 --> 00:34:58.090 align:middle line:84%
would just fluctuate, and it
wouldn't even be continuous

00:34:58.090 --> 00:34:59.400 align:middle line:90%
at x0.

00:34:59.400 --> 00:35:03.360 align:middle line:84%
But once I put this x on,
then it becomes continuous.

00:35:03.360 --> 00:35:07.890 align:middle line:84%
If I put another x,
so if I'm looking

00:35:07.890 --> 00:35:16.528 align:middle line:84%
at f of x equal to x
squared times sine 1 over x.

00:35:16.528 --> 00:35:18.070 align:middle line:84%
Suppose I'm looking
at this function.

00:35:18.070 --> 00:35:23.260 align:middle line:84%
So now I have dampened
the fluctuation even more.

00:35:23.260 --> 00:35:26.670 align:middle line:84%
And so if I came looking at
the difference quotient--

00:35:26.670 --> 00:35:29.730 align:middle line:90%
so I'm looking at this function.

00:35:29.730 --> 00:35:31.210 align:middle line:90%
I should be more careful.

00:35:31.210 --> 00:35:36.610 align:middle line:84%
So again, at 0, I need
to define it separately.

00:35:36.610 --> 00:35:43.270 align:middle line:84%
So I define a function
that is 0 at x equal to 0.

00:35:43.270 --> 00:35:49.880 align:middle line:84%
And then it is x squared
times sine 1 over x otherwise.

00:35:49.880 --> 00:35:53.980 align:middle line:90%


00:35:53.980 --> 00:35:56.010 align:middle line:84%
If I'm looking at
this function, then I

00:35:56.010 --> 00:36:03.490 align:middle line:84%
claim that this function is, in
fact, differentiable at x at 0.

00:36:03.490 --> 00:36:06.850 align:middle line:90%
And so let's look at that.

00:36:06.850 --> 00:36:11.350 align:middle line:84%
So again, I'm looking at
the difference quotient.

00:36:11.350 --> 00:36:14.090 align:middle line:90%
And the value at 0 is 0.

00:36:14.090 --> 00:36:15.195 align:middle line:90%
So I have this.

00:36:15.195 --> 00:36:18.130 align:middle line:90%


00:36:18.130 --> 00:36:25.060 align:middle line:84%
And so this here is now just
x squared sine 1 over x.

00:36:25.060 --> 00:36:27.020 align:middle line:90%
This thing here is then x.

00:36:27.020 --> 00:36:30.700 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that this
difference quotient is just

00:36:30.700 --> 00:36:31.720 align:middle line:90%
this.

00:36:31.720 --> 00:36:38.630 align:middle line:84%
But this here does converge
to 0 as x goes to 0.

00:36:38.630 --> 00:36:41.650 align:middle line:84%
So this function is
actually differentiable.

00:36:41.650 --> 00:36:48.100 align:middle line:84%
It's fluctuates, but it's more
mild the way it fluctuates.

00:36:48.100 --> 00:36:54.140 align:middle line:84%
Now let me get
back to the rules.

00:36:54.140 --> 00:36:59.410 align:middle line:84%
So we proved one rule
that was this sum rule.

00:36:59.410 --> 00:37:03.080 align:middle line:90%


00:37:03.080 --> 00:37:05.480 align:middle line:84%
Then the second rule
we're interested in

00:37:05.480 --> 00:37:08.070 align:middle line:84%
is when we're looking
at the Leibniz rule.

00:37:08.070 --> 00:37:11.180 align:middle line:84%
So we're looking at the
product of these two functions.

00:37:11.180 --> 00:37:17.510 align:middle line:84%
And each function is assumed
to be differentiable at x0.

00:37:17.510 --> 00:37:22.100 align:middle line:84%
And then we claim that the
product function is also

00:37:22.100 --> 00:37:24.240 align:middle line:90%
differentiable at x0.

00:37:24.240 --> 00:37:28.700 align:middle line:84%
And this is the formula
for the derivative.

00:37:28.700 --> 00:37:32.750 align:middle line:84%
To prove this one here,
I need these facts

00:37:32.750 --> 00:37:36.480 align:middle line:84%
that we have now proved that
if it is differentiable,

00:37:36.480 --> 00:37:39.380 align:middle line:84%
then it's also
continuous at that point.

00:37:39.380 --> 00:37:41.695 align:middle line:90%
So I'm going to use that fact.

00:37:41.695 --> 00:37:51.410 align:middle line:90%


00:37:51.410 --> 00:38:01.790 align:middle line:84%
So this is proof
of Leibniz rule.

00:38:01.790 --> 00:38:08.010 align:middle line:90%


00:38:08.010 --> 00:38:11.050 align:middle line:90%
So we have these two functions.

00:38:11.050 --> 00:38:13.537 align:middle line:90%
We're looking at f of x.

00:38:13.537 --> 00:38:14.870 align:middle line:90%
We form the difference quotient.

00:38:14.870 --> 00:38:22.230 align:middle line:90%


00:38:22.230 --> 00:38:25.685 align:middle line:84%
So this is the difference
quotient, x minus x0.

00:38:25.685 --> 00:38:29.580 align:middle line:90%


00:38:29.580 --> 00:38:34.170 align:middle line:84%
We do this trick that we've
done a bunch of times before,

00:38:34.170 --> 00:38:39.090 align:middle line:84%
when we also looked at products
if we had two sequences,

00:38:39.090 --> 00:38:41.430 align:middle line:84%
and we looked at
the sequence that

00:38:41.430 --> 00:38:43.720 align:middle line:90%
was the product of these two.

00:38:43.720 --> 00:38:48.510 align:middle line:90%
So just a reminder that--

00:38:48.510 --> 00:38:49.660 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it's not like--

00:38:49.660 --> 00:38:59.440 align:middle line:90%


00:38:59.440 --> 00:39:04.340 align:middle line:84%
so remember that if you had a
sequence an and a sequence bn,

00:39:04.340 --> 00:39:08.890 align:middle line:84%
and you knew that an converges
to a and bn converges

00:39:08.890 --> 00:39:18.520 align:middle line:84%
to b, then the product here
converges to a times b.

00:39:18.520 --> 00:39:23.320 align:middle line:84%
And when we prove that,
we use this little trick

00:39:23.320 --> 00:39:29.320 align:middle line:84%
that we're splitting the
difference between this

00:39:29.320 --> 00:39:30.830 align:middle line:90%
and this.

00:39:30.830 --> 00:39:34.690 align:middle line:84%
And so I'm going to do
exactly the same trick here.

00:39:34.690 --> 00:39:37.070 align:middle line:84%
So I'm looking at
this thing here.

00:39:37.070 --> 00:39:43.940 align:middle line:84%
And so I write this thing here
as f of x times g of x minus--

00:39:43.940 --> 00:39:48.410 align:middle line:84%
and it doesn't really matter
where you're inserting it.

00:39:48.410 --> 00:39:51.450 align:middle line:84%
So this here is
splitting the difference.

00:39:51.450 --> 00:39:53.020 align:middle line:90%
And then I have to add it again.

00:39:53.020 --> 00:40:02.180 align:middle line:90%


00:40:02.180 --> 00:40:06.590 align:middle line:84%
So this is certainly the
same, just subtracting it

00:40:06.590 --> 00:40:10.100 align:middle line:90%
and adding it right back.

00:40:10.100 --> 00:40:13.170 align:middle line:90%
And now I split this into two.

00:40:13.170 --> 00:40:16.110 align:middle line:90%
So I write this thing here.

00:40:16.110 --> 00:40:20.150 align:middle line:84%
So this fraction,
I split into two.

00:40:20.150 --> 00:40:23.880 align:middle line:84%
And the first one, I take
this one here together.

00:40:23.880 --> 00:40:27.060 align:middle line:90%
And you can factor out a g of x.

00:40:27.060 --> 00:40:36.080 align:middle line:84%
You can write it like this, f
of x minus f of x0, x minus x0.

00:40:36.080 --> 00:40:39.290 align:middle line:90%
So I'm just here.

00:40:39.290 --> 00:40:44.540 align:middle line:84%
I'm factoring out the g of x,
and then I'm left with this.

00:40:44.540 --> 00:40:47.600 align:middle line:84%
And this is keeping the
denominator, like that.

00:40:47.600 --> 00:40:49.930 align:middle line:90%
This is this part here.

00:40:49.930 --> 00:40:52.480 align:middle line:84%
And then I have the
other part here.

00:40:52.480 --> 00:40:56.235 align:middle line:84%
But there, you see that the
f of x0 is factoring out.

00:40:56.235 --> 00:40:58.780 align:middle line:90%


00:40:58.780 --> 00:41:10.180 align:middle line:84%
And then I have g of x minus g
of x0, x minus x0, like that.

00:41:10.180 --> 00:41:17.170 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that
as x goes to x0, well,

00:41:17.170 --> 00:41:20.830 align:middle line:90%
g was continuous at x0.

00:41:20.830 --> 00:41:25.400 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here,
as x goes to x0,

00:41:25.400 --> 00:41:29.930 align:middle line:84%
this thing here
goes to g of x0--

00:41:29.930 --> 00:41:30.620 align:middle line:90%
this one here.

00:41:30.620 --> 00:41:32.810 align:middle line:84%
That was because
g was continuous.

00:41:32.810 --> 00:41:35.930 align:middle line:84%
Because it was differentiable,
so it was also continuous.

00:41:35.930 --> 00:41:38.510 align:middle line:84%
This here goes to
the derivative.

00:41:38.510 --> 00:41:41.350 align:middle line:90%


00:41:41.350 --> 00:41:47.780 align:middle line:84%
And the second thing here
this is just constant.

00:41:47.780 --> 00:41:55.260 align:middle line:84%
And this goes to the
derivative, like that.

00:41:55.260 --> 00:42:01.040 align:middle line:84%
So what we have proven this
here is as x goes to x0.

00:42:01.040 --> 00:42:04.400 align:middle line:84%
So you see that we have
proven that this difference

00:42:04.400 --> 00:42:09.350 align:middle line:84%
quotient here for the
product has a limit.

00:42:09.350 --> 00:42:11.970 align:middle line:90%
And this is what the limit is.

00:42:11.970 --> 00:42:15.200 align:middle line:84%
And so this means that the
product is differentiable.

00:42:15.200 --> 00:42:17.820 align:middle line:90%
And this here is the derivative.

00:42:17.820 --> 00:42:21.180 align:middle line:84%
And that's exactly
the Leibniz formula,

00:42:21.180 --> 00:42:24.510 align:middle line:84%
which was this over
here, this formula here.

00:42:24.510 --> 00:42:27.320 align:middle line:90%


00:42:27.320 --> 00:42:34.490 align:middle line:84%
The next thing is that we
want to prove the next rule is

00:42:34.490 --> 00:42:37.370 align:middle line:90%
like this quotient rule.

00:42:37.370 --> 00:42:40.165 align:middle line:84%
So let me prove
the quotient rule.

00:42:40.165 --> 00:42:58.320 align:middle line:90%


00:42:58.320 --> 00:43:04.680 align:middle line:84%
So Leibniz and Newton
was the one that

00:43:04.680 --> 00:43:09.993 align:middle line:90%
was responsible for calculus.

00:43:09.993 --> 00:43:13.770 align:middle line:90%


00:43:13.770 --> 00:43:16.110 align:middle line:84%
And so then the next
thing I want to prove

00:43:16.110 --> 00:43:17.950 align:middle line:90%
is this quotient rule.

00:43:17.950 --> 00:43:27.870 align:middle line:90%


00:43:27.870 --> 00:43:31.535 align:middle line:84%
And so, again, you have
these two functions, f and g.

00:43:31.535 --> 00:43:36.360 align:middle line:90%


00:43:36.360 --> 00:43:49.190 align:middle line:84%
And they are
differentiable at x0.

00:43:49.190 --> 00:43:58.430 align:middle line:84%
And I'm also assuming that g
here at x0 is not equal to x.

00:43:58.430 --> 00:44:02.800 align:middle line:84%
Let's just assume that g is
not equal to 0 everywhere.

00:44:02.800 --> 00:44:08.420 align:middle line:84%
It's different
from 0 everywhere.

00:44:08.420 --> 00:44:13.870 align:middle line:90%


00:44:13.870 --> 00:44:18.280 align:middle line:84%
And then the quotient
rule says that if you're

00:44:18.280 --> 00:44:25.210 align:middle line:84%
looking at the quotient here and
you take the derivative of the--

00:44:25.210 --> 00:44:29.320 align:middle line:84%
so it say that if you're
looking at the quotient here--

00:44:29.320 --> 00:44:33.910 align:middle line:84%
so the quotient will say that
if you're looking at this thing

00:44:33.910 --> 00:44:37.700 align:middle line:84%
here, this now makes sense
because g does not vanish.

00:44:37.700 --> 00:44:48.470 align:middle line:84%
This here is
differentiable at x0.

00:44:48.470 --> 00:44:56.480 align:middle line:84%
And the derivative of
this function at x0

00:44:56.480 --> 00:44:59.270 align:middle line:84%
is given by the
following formula,

00:44:59.270 --> 00:45:07.700 align:middle line:84%
that it is the derivative
of f at x0 times g of x0

00:45:07.700 --> 00:45:20.100 align:middle line:84%
minus f at x0 times g prime
at x0 divided by g squared.

00:45:20.100 --> 00:45:23.460 align:middle line:90%
So g of x minus 0 times itself--

00:45:23.460 --> 00:45:24.965 align:middle line:90%
I'll write that as a square.

00:45:24.965 --> 00:45:28.370 align:middle line:90%


00:45:28.370 --> 00:45:30.530 align:middle line:84%
Write this here
again-- this here,

00:45:30.530 --> 00:45:35.750 align:middle line:84%
this is just g of
x0 times g of x0.

00:45:35.750 --> 00:45:40.360 align:middle line:90%


00:45:40.360 --> 00:45:44.475 align:middle line:90%
So now let's try to prove that.

00:45:44.475 --> 00:46:09.550 align:middle line:90%


00:46:09.550 --> 00:46:14.380 align:middle line:84%
So we're looking at
f of x like this.

00:46:14.380 --> 00:46:19.540 align:middle line:84%
At x minus-- so this is
the difference version--

00:46:19.540 --> 00:46:24.920 align:middle line:90%
at x0 divided by x minus x0.

00:46:24.920 --> 00:46:26.530 align:middle line:90%
That's the difference equation.

00:46:26.530 --> 00:46:40.490 align:middle line:84%
And so written out, this is
f of x g of x minus f of x0

00:46:40.490 --> 00:46:46.580 align:middle line:90%
divided by g of x0 x minus x0.

00:46:46.580 --> 00:46:52.110 align:middle line:84%
So let me put this on a fraction
with a common denominator.

00:46:52.110 --> 00:46:56.730 align:middle line:84%
So if I do that, then
this thing here is--

00:46:56.730 --> 00:47:01.940 align:middle line:84%
so then I'm
multiplying by g of x0

00:47:01.940 --> 00:47:05.690 align:middle line:84%
both in the numerator
and the denominator here.

00:47:05.690 --> 00:47:12.350 align:middle line:84%
So I'm getting f
of x times g of x0.

00:47:12.350 --> 00:47:14.690 align:middle line:84%
And then here, I'm
multiplying by g

00:47:14.690 --> 00:47:18.470 align:middle line:84%
of x in both numerator and
denominator, so getting

00:47:18.470 --> 00:47:22.670 align:middle line:90%
this thing here, g of x.

00:47:22.670 --> 00:47:33.230 align:middle line:84%
And then it becomes x minus
x0 and then g of x, g of x0,

00:47:33.230 --> 00:47:33.775 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:47:33.775 --> 00:47:37.260 align:middle line:90%


00:47:37.260 --> 00:47:43.900 align:middle line:84%
And so now you can write
this thing here as--

00:47:43.900 --> 00:47:49.770 align:middle line:84%
and so now you do the
same trick as before.

00:47:49.770 --> 00:47:54.540 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I could have gotten
a way slightly easier

00:47:54.540 --> 00:47:59.730 align:middle line:84%
with looking at a special
case of this quotient rule,

00:47:59.730 --> 00:48:02.260 align:middle line:84%
where f was a
constant function 1.

00:48:02.260 --> 00:48:04.480 align:middle line:90%
So I could do that first.

00:48:04.480 --> 00:48:07.890 align:middle line:84%
And then the general
case, I could then from--

00:48:07.890 --> 00:48:13.750 align:middle line:84%
get from this special case
together with Leibniz rule.

00:48:13.750 --> 00:48:16.420 align:middle line:84%
It's most often I want
to do it together anyway,

00:48:16.420 --> 00:48:18.400 align:middle line:84%
but if you have
to do it together,

00:48:18.400 --> 00:48:22.050 align:middle line:84%
you have to use the same
trick that we just did.

00:48:22.050 --> 00:48:39.280 align:middle line:84%
So we're using that over
here, so f of g of x0 minus

00:48:39.280 --> 00:48:57.520 align:middle line:84%
and then f of x0, g of
x0, Plus f of x0 g of x0

00:48:57.520 --> 00:49:03.170 align:middle line:84%
minus f of x0 g of
x-- so this is, again,

00:49:03.170 --> 00:49:05.900 align:middle line:84%
where I'm subtracting in the
denominator or something,

00:49:05.900 --> 00:49:09.220 align:middle line:84%
and then I'm adding it
back up immediately.

00:49:09.220 --> 00:49:19.260 align:middle line:90%
So I have this, like that.

00:49:19.260 --> 00:49:21.940 align:middle line:90%


00:49:21.940 --> 00:49:27.800 align:middle line:84%
And so now if you do
that, then you see that--

00:49:27.800 --> 00:49:33.080 align:middle line:84%
and now you split it up,
again, into two fractions.

00:49:33.080 --> 00:49:35.630 align:middle line:90%
So we split it up.

00:49:35.630 --> 00:49:40.490 align:middle line:84%
And so this thing here,
this thing here, but there,

00:49:40.490 --> 00:49:43.590 align:middle line:84%
you see that there's a g
of x here that factor out.

00:49:43.590 --> 00:49:47.420 align:middle line:90%
So this is equal to g of x0.

00:49:47.420 --> 00:49:54.080 align:middle line:84%
And then you have f of
x minus f of x0 and then

00:49:54.080 --> 00:50:03.680 align:middle line:84%
x minus x0, g of x,
g of x0, like that.

00:50:03.680 --> 00:50:09.020 align:middle line:84%
And for the second one, you
see that there, you also

00:50:09.020 --> 00:50:11.120 align:middle line:90%
have something that factor out.

00:50:11.120 --> 00:50:17.420 align:middle line:90%
And this is f of x0, like that.

00:50:17.420 --> 00:50:23.840 align:middle line:84%
And you're getting
g of x0 minus g

00:50:23.840 --> 00:50:37.840 align:middle line:84%
of x over x minus x0, g
of x, g of x0, like that.

00:50:37.840 --> 00:50:46.030 align:middle line:84%
And so now I can make
this looks nicer.

00:50:46.030 --> 00:50:50.440 align:middle line:84%
I can, this one here,
cancel with that.

00:50:50.440 --> 00:50:53.050 align:middle line:84%
And so I can write
this thing here

00:50:53.050 --> 00:51:03.820 align:middle line:84%
as 1 over g of x f of x minus
f of x0 divided by x minus x0.

00:51:03.820 --> 00:51:06.150 align:middle line:90%
So let's take care of this here.

00:51:06.150 --> 00:51:08.710 align:middle line:90%


00:51:08.710 --> 00:51:16.100 align:middle line:84%
Here, I will write it as I
will take this one here out.

00:51:16.100 --> 00:51:26.200 align:middle line:84%
So I'll write it as f of
x0 of x times g of x0.

00:51:26.200 --> 00:51:29.090 align:middle line:84%
And then I'm left
with this thing here.

00:51:29.090 --> 00:51:31.430 align:middle line:84%
And what I don't love
about this thing here

00:51:31.430 --> 00:51:34.340 align:middle line:84%
is it's not quite the
difference quotient

00:51:34.340 --> 00:51:37.070 align:middle line:84%
because the order of
these two is wrong.

00:51:37.070 --> 00:51:39.930 align:middle line:90%
So I switched the order.

00:51:39.930 --> 00:51:46.170 align:middle line:84%
But if I switch the order, then
I have to pick up a minus sign.

00:51:46.170 --> 00:51:47.880 align:middle line:90%
So I get minus here.

00:51:47.880 --> 00:51:58.650 align:middle line:84%
And now it is g of x, g of
x0, x minus x0, like that.

00:51:58.650 --> 00:52:05.150 align:middle line:84%
And now you see that
as x goes to x0,

00:52:05.150 --> 00:52:12.620 align:middle line:84%
so now as x goes to x0, well,
this one here, the function

00:52:12.620 --> 00:52:13.530 align:middle line:90%
was differentiable.

00:52:13.530 --> 00:52:14.730 align:middle line:90%
So it's also continuous.

00:52:14.730 --> 00:52:18.740 align:middle line:90%
So this goes to 1 over g of x0.

00:52:18.740 --> 00:52:25.640 align:middle line:84%
This one here just goes
to the derivative at x0.

00:52:25.640 --> 00:52:29.010 align:middle line:84%
This one here goes to--
again, because the function

00:52:29.010 --> 00:52:33.540 align:middle line:84%
is continuous, this
goes to minus f of x0.

00:52:33.540 --> 00:52:36.495 align:middle line:84%
And then it's what I
wrote before as g squared.

00:52:36.495 --> 00:52:40.920 align:middle line:90%
It's g of x0 times itself.

00:52:40.920 --> 00:52:47.910 align:middle line:84%
And then this thing here goes
to the derivative of x0 at 0.

00:52:47.910 --> 00:52:53.410 align:middle line:84%
And now if I want to, I can
rewrite this thing here.

00:52:53.410 --> 00:52:56.470 align:middle line:84%
If I want to put it back
on the common denominator,

00:52:56.470 --> 00:53:00.570 align:middle line:84%
then I have to multiply in
the numerator and denominator

00:53:00.570 --> 00:53:02.320 align:middle line:90%
by g of x0.

00:53:02.320 --> 00:53:10.170 align:middle line:84%
If I do this, I get f
prime of x0, g of x0,

00:53:10.170 --> 00:53:15.640 align:middle line:84%
and then I get g squared
of x0 in the denominator.

00:53:15.640 --> 00:53:25.170 align:middle line:84%
And then here it's just those
two minus f of x0 g prime of x0.

00:53:25.170 --> 00:53:29.440 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that this
here is exactly this formula

00:53:29.440 --> 00:53:31.540 align:middle line:90%
here, this quotient rule.

00:53:31.540 --> 00:53:38.290 align:middle line:84%
So this proof, that if you
take two functions, the one

00:53:38.290 --> 00:53:41.270 align:middle line:84%
you have in the denominator,
if that is nonvanishing,

00:53:41.270 --> 00:53:43.600 align:middle line:90%
So You can form the quotient.

00:53:43.600 --> 00:53:47.300 align:middle line:84%
And if each of these two
functions is differentiable,

00:53:47.300 --> 00:53:50.150 align:middle line:84%
then the quotient is
also differentiable.

00:53:50.150 --> 00:53:53.600 align:middle line:84%
And this is the formula
for the derivative.

00:53:53.600 --> 00:53:57.250 align:middle line:84%
So now why is this already
really, really useful?

00:53:57.250 --> 00:54:11.440 align:middle line:84%
So we calculated-- so we started
with the example of where

00:54:11.440 --> 00:54:13.880 align:middle line:90%
f is a constant.

00:54:13.880 --> 00:54:17.050 align:middle line:84%
And we saw that
it's differentiable,

00:54:17.050 --> 00:54:19.060 align:middle line:90%
and the derivative is 0.

00:54:19.060 --> 00:54:24.740 align:middle line:84%
Then the second example we had
was where the function was x,

00:54:24.740 --> 00:54:26.810 align:middle line:84%
and we saw that it
was differentiable

00:54:26.810 --> 00:54:29.580 align:middle line:90%
and the derivative is 1.

00:54:29.580 --> 00:54:32.160 align:middle line:90%
If you now take--

00:54:32.160 --> 00:54:36.570 align:middle line:90%
if you now take ax times--

00:54:36.570 --> 00:54:39.860 align:middle line:84%
so let's just take ax
as the next example.

00:54:39.860 --> 00:54:45.300 align:middle line:84%
This is like a constant
function times this function.

00:54:45.300 --> 00:54:48.140 align:middle line:84%
So Leibniz rule--
so if f of x is

00:54:48.140 --> 00:54:51.750 align:middle line:84%
equal to a times x,
where A is a constant,

00:54:51.750 --> 00:54:55.040 align:middle line:84%
Leibniz will say that the
product of two differentiable

00:54:55.040 --> 00:54:59.480 align:middle line:84%
function is differentiable,
and the derivative of this

00:54:59.480 --> 00:55:01.398 align:middle line:90%
is the derivative of that.

00:55:01.398 --> 00:55:03.690 align:middle line:84%
But the derivative of that,
that's a constant function.

00:55:03.690 --> 00:55:04.380 align:middle line:90%
So that's 0.

00:55:04.380 --> 00:55:06.300 align:middle line:84%
So I don't even have
to think about that.

00:55:06.300 --> 00:55:09.710 align:middle line:84%
So it's just the a
times the derivative

00:55:09.710 --> 00:55:10.710 align:middle line:90%
of the second function.

00:55:10.710 --> 00:55:11.460 align:middle line:90%
But that's one.

00:55:11.460 --> 00:55:15.660 align:middle line:84%
So this here is the
derivative of that.

00:55:15.660 --> 00:55:21.440 align:middle line:84%
And the next example would be
that you're looking at ax plus,

00:55:21.440 --> 00:55:22.765 align:middle line:90%
say, b.

00:55:22.765 --> 00:55:25.050 align:middle line:90%
f of x is equal to this.

00:55:25.050 --> 00:55:28.450 align:middle line:90%
Then you can use the sum plus--

00:55:28.450 --> 00:55:31.030 align:middle line:90%
we know what each of these is.

00:55:31.030 --> 00:55:34.300 align:middle line:84%
So you get that this one
here is also differentiable.

00:55:34.300 --> 00:55:38.790 align:middle line:84%
And the derivative of this
function here is also just a.

00:55:38.790 --> 00:55:43.150 align:middle line:84%
And you can continue like
this, that if you take--

00:55:43.150 --> 00:55:47.500 align:middle line:84%
and if you now
have a polynomial,

00:55:47.500 --> 00:55:50.640 align:middle line:84%
suppose you take
a to the power n.

00:55:50.640 --> 00:55:55.950 align:middle line:84%
So if f of x is
x to the power n,

00:55:55.950 --> 00:55:58.140 align:middle line:84%
then you can think
about this thing

00:55:58.140 --> 00:56:03.330 align:middle line:84%
here as x times x
times x times x.

00:56:03.330 --> 00:56:05.800 align:middle line:84%
And you can use
the Leibniz rule.

00:56:05.800 --> 00:56:08.770 align:middle line:84%
And so if you use
the Leibniz rule,

00:56:08.770 --> 00:56:12.720 align:middle line:84%
so you just do it first
in the case where f of x

00:56:12.720 --> 00:56:16.660 align:middle line:84%
is equal to x squared, you can
think about this as x times x.

00:56:16.660 --> 00:56:18.970 align:middle line:84%
These are two
differentiable functions.

00:56:18.970 --> 00:56:23.190 align:middle line:84%
So the derivative here is
now the derivative of this.

00:56:23.190 --> 00:56:26.130 align:middle line:84%
So that's 1 times
the other function.

00:56:26.130 --> 00:56:30.480 align:middle line:84%
Plus you keep this one here and
take the derivative of that.

00:56:30.480 --> 00:56:31.590 align:middle line:90%
So this is this.

00:56:31.590 --> 00:56:35.420 align:middle line:90%
So this is 2 times x.

00:56:35.420 --> 00:56:40.520 align:middle line:84%
And so if you take this function
here using Leibniz rule.

00:56:40.520 --> 00:56:43.700 align:middle line:84%
In this case, the derivative
is differentiable,

00:56:43.700 --> 00:56:50.065 align:middle line:84%
and the derivative is n times
x to the power n minus 1.

00:56:50.065 --> 00:56:55.340 align:middle line:90%


00:56:55.340 --> 00:56:58.280 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, even
more generally,

00:56:58.280 --> 00:57:05.300 align:middle line:84%
just using the sum
and the Leibniz rule,

00:57:05.300 --> 00:57:13.220 align:middle line:84%
if you take any polynomial
an xn plus an minus 1 xn

00:57:13.220 --> 00:57:20.130 align:middle line:84%
minus 1 down to the last thing
is being a constant-- if you

00:57:20.130 --> 00:57:24.000 align:middle line:84%
take a polynomial like
this just using the Leibniz

00:57:24.000 --> 00:57:29.190 align:middle line:84%
rule and the sum rule,
using those repeatedly,

00:57:29.190 --> 00:57:32.190 align:middle line:84%
we know that this
is differentiable

00:57:32.190 --> 00:57:34.890 align:middle line:84%
and the derivative
is just like the sum

00:57:34.890 --> 00:57:36.190 align:middle line:90%
of the derivative of these.

00:57:36.190 --> 00:57:42.900 align:middle line:84%
So this is going to be an times
n times x to the power n minus 1

00:57:42.900 --> 00:57:51.420 align:middle line:84%
plus n minus 1 times
n minus 1 xn minus 2.

00:57:51.420 --> 00:57:54.550 align:middle line:84%
And then this one here,
the derivative is 0.

00:57:54.550 --> 00:57:58.590 align:middle line:84%
So the last one you're getting
something in nontrivial form

00:57:58.590 --> 00:58:01.840 align:middle line:90%
is a1.

00:58:01.840 --> 00:58:04.590 align:middle line:84%
So this is just using
sum and Leibniz rule.

00:58:04.590 --> 00:58:21.190 align:middle line:84%
And so this is just using
the sum plus Leibniz rule

00:58:21.190 --> 00:58:21.910 align:middle line:90%
repeatedly.

00:58:21.910 --> 00:58:28.400 align:middle line:90%


00:58:28.400 --> 00:58:33.430 align:middle line:84%
Now likewise, if you
take a rational function,

00:58:33.430 --> 00:58:36.560 align:middle line:84%
so meaning that if
you take something--

00:58:36.560 --> 00:58:41.800 align:middle line:84%
if f of x is equal
to some polynomial--

00:58:41.800 --> 00:58:45.760 align:middle line:90%


00:58:45.760 --> 00:58:54.640 align:middle line:84%
so let's go p of x divided
by q of x, so where this here

00:58:54.640 --> 00:59:03.790 align:middle line:90%
is a polynomial and so is that.

00:59:03.790 --> 00:59:07.540 align:middle line:84%
So now you can use
the quotient rule.

00:59:07.540 --> 00:59:15.680 align:middle line:90%


00:59:15.680 --> 00:59:17.180 align:middle line:84%
So the quotient
rule will tell you

00:59:17.180 --> 00:59:21.170 align:middle line:84%
that as long as you are looking
at point where this here

00:59:21.170 --> 00:59:25.040 align:middle line:84%
does not vanish, so then
the quotient here is also

00:59:25.040 --> 00:59:28.250 align:middle line:84%
differentiable, and
it gives you a formula

00:59:28.250 --> 00:59:31.010 align:middle line:84%
for the derivative in terms
of the derivative of each

00:59:31.010 --> 00:59:31.950 align:middle line:90%
of these two.

00:59:31.950 --> 00:59:35.480 align:middle line:84%
And each of those two, they
can be calculated like that.

00:59:35.480 --> 00:59:42.200 align:middle line:84%
So you see, already now, we
have quite the derivative

00:59:42.200 --> 00:59:43.620 align:middle line:90%
of a lot of functions.

00:59:43.620 --> 00:59:47.040 align:middle line:84%
We have of all function and
of all rational functions.

00:59:47.040 --> 00:59:51.020 align:middle line:84%
Rational functions, again,
are quotients of a polynomial

00:59:51.020 --> 00:59:54.770 align:middle line:90%
by other polynomial.

00:59:54.770 --> 01:00:00.680 align:middle line:84%
So now the next rule that
we want to talk about

01:00:00.680 --> 01:00:03.340 align:middle line:90%
is the chain rule.

01:00:03.340 --> 01:00:07.220 align:middle line:90%


01:00:07.220 --> 01:00:09.950 align:middle line:90%
So what is the chain rule?

01:00:09.950 --> 01:00:14.550 align:middle line:84%
So the chain rule is a little
bit different from those three

01:00:14.550 --> 01:00:16.410 align:middle line:90%
rules here.

01:00:16.410 --> 01:00:22.200 align:middle line:84%
And it is where you take the
composition of functions.

01:00:22.200 --> 01:00:24.400 align:middle line:90%
So the next is the chain rule.

01:00:24.400 --> 01:00:30.060 align:middle line:90%


01:00:30.060 --> 01:00:40.900 align:middle line:84%
And again, this is about
composition of functions.

01:00:40.900 --> 01:00:44.340 align:middle line:90%


01:00:44.340 --> 01:00:51.990 align:middle line:84%
So I have a function f
that goes, say, from--

01:00:51.990 --> 01:00:54.180 align:middle line:84%
to say that it goes
from some interval a

01:00:54.180 --> 01:01:00.840 align:middle line:84%
to b into another
interval from c to d.

01:01:00.840 --> 01:01:06.300 align:middle line:84%
And then I have a function g
that goes from this interval

01:01:06.300 --> 01:01:20.450 align:middle line:84%
here into R because g is
defined whatever the image of f

01:01:20.450 --> 01:01:25.950 align:middle line:84%
always, if it's in the set,
this is where g is defined.

01:01:25.950 --> 01:01:33.350 align:middle line:84%
Then you have that you can form
if you take some x in here--

01:01:33.350 --> 01:01:39.450 align:middle line:84%
so if x here is in a to b,
then this here makes sense.

01:01:39.450 --> 01:01:43.020 align:middle line:90%
And this is now an element here.

01:01:43.020 --> 01:01:45.120 align:middle line:90%
So this is where g is defined.

01:01:45.120 --> 01:01:47.360 align:middle line:90%
So this here makes sense.

01:01:47.360 --> 01:01:51.060 align:middle line:84%
And this is now what we
call the composition.

01:01:51.060 --> 01:01:52.920 align:middle line:90%
And we write it like this.

01:01:52.920 --> 01:01:58.220 align:middle line:84%
It's important to write
it in the correct order.

01:01:58.220 --> 01:02:00.430 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
composition function.

01:02:00.430 --> 01:02:08.330 align:middle line:90%


01:02:08.330 --> 01:02:10.870 align:middle line:84%
So now the chain rule
is the following.

01:02:10.870 --> 01:02:23.730 align:middle line:90%


01:02:23.730 --> 01:02:25.790 align:middle line:84%
So the chain rule is
a foreign theorem.

01:02:25.790 --> 01:02:36.480 align:middle line:90%


01:02:36.480 --> 01:02:53.310 align:middle line:84%
Then if f is
differentiable at x0

01:02:53.310 --> 01:03:09.010 align:middle line:84%
and g is differentiable
at y0, where

01:03:09.010 --> 01:03:17.660 align:middle line:84%
y0 is equal to the value of f
at x0, then the composition--

01:03:17.660 --> 01:03:20.650 align:middle line:84%
then the composition
of these two functions

01:03:20.650 --> 01:03:25.720 align:middle line:84%
is differentiable at
x0, and the derivative

01:03:25.720 --> 01:03:31.270 align:middle line:84%
is equal to the derivative
of g at y0 times

01:03:31.270 --> 01:03:34.940 align:middle line:90%
the derivative of f at x0.

01:03:34.940 --> 01:03:36.790 align:middle line:90%
So this is the chain rule.

01:03:36.790 --> 01:03:39.760 align:middle line:84%
The chain rule says that
the composition is also

01:03:39.760 --> 01:03:43.720 align:middle line:84%
differentiable at
x0, and this is

01:03:43.720 --> 01:03:47.840 align:middle line:90%
the formula for the derivative.

01:03:47.840 --> 01:03:50.230 align:middle line:90%
Let's try to prove that.

01:03:50.230 --> 01:03:54.940 align:middle line:84%
And so, in this case,
it's useful to divide up

01:03:54.940 --> 01:03:56.883 align:middle line:90%
to two cases.

01:03:56.883 --> 01:04:03.580 align:middle line:90%


01:04:03.580 --> 01:04:07.520 align:middle line:84%
And the two cases to
divide up to-- so let

01:04:07.520 --> 01:04:12.030 align:middle line:84%
me just look at a
special case first,

01:04:12.030 --> 01:04:16.940 align:middle line:84%
and then once we understand
that, the general case will

01:04:16.940 --> 01:04:17.960 align:middle line:90%
be clear.

01:04:17.960 --> 01:04:20.370 align:middle line:90%
So let's make one assumption.

01:04:20.370 --> 01:04:21.415 align:middle line:90%
So let's try to prove it.

01:04:21.415 --> 01:04:25.310 align:middle line:90%


01:04:25.310 --> 01:04:34.736 align:middle line:84%
But we assume first
that the derivative--

01:04:34.736 --> 01:04:37.250 align:middle line:90%


01:04:37.250 --> 01:04:41.630 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to assume that
the derivative at x0

01:04:41.630 --> 01:04:43.410 align:middle line:90%
is not equal to 0.

01:04:43.410 --> 01:04:48.350 align:middle line:84%
So I'm assuming that, first,
what does this guarantee me?

01:04:48.350 --> 01:04:53.150 align:middle line:84%
Well, remember that the
derivative is the limit

01:04:53.150 --> 01:04:54.355 align:middle line:90%
of this difference quotient.

01:04:54.355 --> 01:04:58.220 align:middle line:90%


01:04:58.220 --> 01:05:01.880 align:middle line:90%
So this is the limit.

01:05:01.880 --> 01:05:06.060 align:middle line:84%
If this here is not
equal to 0, this

01:05:06.060 --> 01:05:09.790 align:middle line:84%
means that when x
is very close to x0,

01:05:09.790 --> 01:05:15.900 align:middle line:84%
this thing here is very
close to this thing that

01:05:15.900 --> 01:05:17.530 align:middle line:90%
is not equal to 0.

01:05:17.530 --> 01:05:22.140 align:middle line:84%
But then it means that if
you are very close to x0,

01:05:22.140 --> 01:05:25.660 align:middle line:90%
f of x cannot be equal to.

01:05:25.660 --> 01:05:31.800 align:middle line:84%
So if you have this here,
this implies that f of x

01:05:31.800 --> 01:05:36.360 align:middle line:90%
is not equal to x0 for--

01:05:36.360 --> 01:05:52.320 align:middle line:84%
sorry, it's not equal to f of x0
for x sufficiently close to x0.

01:05:52.320 --> 01:05:55.540 align:middle line:84%
I'm always assuming, of
course, that x is not

01:05:55.540 --> 01:05:59.820 align:middle line:90%
but x is not equal to 0.

01:05:59.820 --> 01:06:04.760 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to first
make this assumption.

01:06:04.760 --> 01:06:07.630 align:middle line:84%
And if I make this assumption,
what I get out of it

01:06:07.630 --> 01:06:11.030 align:middle line:84%
is that this thing here
is not equal to that.

01:06:11.030 --> 01:06:12.740 align:middle line:90%
Why is this useful?

01:06:12.740 --> 01:06:17.590 align:middle line:84%
Because now I can actually look
at this difference and I can

01:06:17.590 --> 01:06:18.800 align:middle line:90%
divide by it.

01:06:18.800 --> 01:06:33.220 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to just to make
things a little bit clearer.

01:06:33.220 --> 01:06:35.153 align:middle line:90%
So I have my function.

01:06:35.153 --> 01:06:39.400 align:middle line:90%


01:06:39.400 --> 01:06:42.220 align:middle line:90%
So this here is f.

01:06:42.220 --> 01:06:45.010 align:middle line:90%
And here I have g.

01:06:45.010 --> 01:06:47.500 align:middle line:90%
Here, I have x0.

01:06:47.500 --> 01:06:52.780 align:middle line:84%
But under f, it's taken
to this, which is f of x0.

01:06:52.780 --> 01:06:56.900 align:middle line:84%
But this I also
will denote by y0.

01:06:56.900 --> 01:06:59.930 align:middle line:84%
So I'm denoting just
to make things clearer,

01:06:59.930 --> 01:07:03.870 align:middle line:90%
y0 is just the value here.

01:07:03.870 --> 01:07:09.180 align:middle line:90%
And then I will use for--

01:07:09.180 --> 01:07:13.260 align:middle line:90%
f of x I will denote by y.

01:07:13.260 --> 01:07:17.560 align:middle line:84%
So now I'm looking at
the difference quotient.

01:07:17.560 --> 01:07:20.550 align:middle line:84%
So I'm looking at
f of-- sorry, I'm

01:07:20.550 --> 01:07:34.650 align:middle line:84%
looking at g of f of x minus
g of f of x0 x minus x0.

01:07:34.650 --> 01:07:37.620 align:middle line:84%
That's what I'm
supposed to look at.

01:07:37.620 --> 01:07:45.160 align:middle line:84%
And I can write this
thing here as g of y

01:07:45.160 --> 01:07:47.680 align:middle line:90%
because this here I also call y.

01:07:47.680 --> 01:07:53.190 align:middle line:84%
So you can write it
like this g of y0.

01:07:53.190 --> 01:07:58.930 align:middle line:84%
And then I will write
it as y minus y0,

01:07:58.930 --> 01:08:01.330 align:middle line:84%
but I didn't have this
in the denominator

01:08:01.330 --> 01:08:05.860 align:middle line:84%
up here, so I have to
multiply it back on.

01:08:05.860 --> 01:08:10.630 align:middle line:84%
And then I still have
to divide by that.

01:08:10.630 --> 01:08:13.060 align:middle line:90%
So I can write it like this.

01:08:13.060 --> 01:08:15.357 align:middle line:90%
This here I'm happy with.

01:08:15.357 --> 01:08:16.899 align:middle line:84%
Get to this in just
a second, but I'm

01:08:16.899 --> 01:08:18.609 align:middle line:90%
happy with this expression.

01:08:18.609 --> 01:08:23.359 align:middle line:84%
The other one I really want to
put it back in, in terms of f.

01:08:23.359 --> 01:08:25.005 align:middle line:90%
So I'm writing this in here.

01:08:25.005 --> 01:08:33.399 align:middle line:90%


01:08:33.399 --> 01:08:35.319 align:middle line:84%
And this thing
here, I really want

01:08:35.319 --> 01:08:37.700 align:middle line:90%
to put it back in terms of f.

01:08:37.700 --> 01:08:44.649 align:middle line:84%
So if I do that, I write it as f
of dx minus f of x0 x minus x0.

01:08:44.649 --> 01:08:47.560 align:middle line:90%


01:08:47.560 --> 01:08:56.859 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that
as x goes to x0, well,

01:08:56.859 --> 01:09:03.689 align:middle line:84%
as x goes to x0, because the
function f was continuous at x0,

01:09:03.689 --> 01:09:09.229 align:middle line:84%
it means that if x goes to x0,
then the value at x, which is y,

01:09:09.229 --> 01:09:11.069 align:middle line:90%
will go to the value at x0.

01:09:11.069 --> 01:09:20.363 align:middle line:84%
So when x goes to x0, we
have that y goes to y0.

01:09:20.363 --> 01:09:23.779 align:middle line:90%


01:09:23.779 --> 01:09:31.290 align:middle line:84%
So this means that this thing
here, this here converges.

01:09:31.290 --> 01:09:34.050 align:middle line:84%
That's just because the
function f is differentiable.

01:09:34.050 --> 01:09:37.620 align:middle line:84%
So this here will converge
to the derivative.

01:09:37.620 --> 01:09:44.660 align:middle line:84%
So the second factor here is
converging to f prime at x0.

01:09:44.660 --> 01:09:47.660 align:middle line:84%
The first factor is-- but
now you see that we just

01:09:47.660 --> 01:09:50.729 align:middle line:90%
argued that y goes to y0.

01:09:50.729 --> 01:09:53.340 align:middle line:84%
So this is also a
difference quotient.

01:09:53.340 --> 01:09:55.070 align:middle line:84%
But it's a difference
quotient for g.

01:09:55.070 --> 01:09:58.710 align:middle line:84%
And since y goes to y0,
this difference quotient

01:09:58.710 --> 01:10:04.365 align:middle line:84%
here goes to the
derivative of g at y0.

01:10:04.365 --> 01:10:07.740 align:middle line:90%


01:10:07.740 --> 01:10:11.110 align:middle line:84%
But that's exactly the formula
that we wanted to prove,

01:10:11.110 --> 01:10:13.530 align:middle line:84%
except that we
made one assumption

01:10:13.530 --> 01:10:21.180 align:middle line:84%
that the derivative of f
at x0 was not equal to 0.

01:10:21.180 --> 01:10:26.400 align:middle line:84%
We made that assumption only
so that this number here

01:10:26.400 --> 01:10:28.540 align:middle line:90%
was not equal to 0.

01:10:28.540 --> 01:10:32.250 align:middle line:90%
And so we could divide by it.

01:10:32.250 --> 01:10:40.890 align:middle line:84%
But actually, otherwise,
if you, for some reason,

01:10:40.890 --> 01:10:48.300 align:middle line:84%
if y was not equal
to y0, but then

01:10:48.300 --> 01:10:51.000 align:middle line:84%
this formula here
would still hold.

01:10:51.000 --> 01:11:00.190 align:middle line:84%
So it's only the possibility
that y could be equal to y0.

01:11:00.190 --> 01:11:02.590 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that
if you were just

01:11:02.590 --> 01:11:07.970 align:middle line:84%
looking at the difference
quotient g of f--

01:11:07.970 --> 01:11:13.900 align:middle line:90%
g of y minus--

01:11:13.900 --> 01:11:19.690 align:middle line:90%
sorry, g of f of x minus--

01:11:19.690 --> 01:11:22.070 align:middle line:84%
so this is the
difference quotient.

01:11:22.070 --> 01:11:31.910 align:middle line:84%
That is the one we really have
to look at for the composition.

01:11:31.910 --> 01:11:36.670 align:middle line:90%
And this is what we also call--

01:11:36.670 --> 01:11:39.730 align:middle line:84%
this thing here is
what we called y0.

01:11:39.730 --> 01:11:41.775 align:middle line:84%
This thing here
is what we call y.

01:11:41.775 --> 01:11:45.250 align:middle line:90%


01:11:45.250 --> 01:11:54.690 align:middle line:84%
And the only case we haven't
dealt with is where f prime of 0

01:11:54.690 --> 01:12:03.540 align:middle line:84%
is equal to 0, and
y is equal to y0.

01:12:03.540 --> 01:12:06.420 align:middle line:90%
This here, again, was f of x.

01:12:06.420 --> 01:12:09.390 align:middle line:84%
And this here was
equal to f of x0.

01:12:09.390 --> 01:12:15.210 align:middle line:84%
So this is only this case
here we haven't dealt with.

01:12:15.210 --> 01:12:21.840 align:middle line:84%
But you see that if it
so happened that f of x

01:12:21.840 --> 01:12:25.680 align:middle line:84%
was equal to f of 0, then
this difference quotient here,

01:12:25.680 --> 01:12:28.800 align:middle line:84%
the denominator
would trivially be 0.

01:12:28.800 --> 01:12:33.720 align:middle line:84%
And so you want to prove we
have that if this here was not

01:12:33.720 --> 01:12:36.180 align:middle line:84%
equal to 0, then we
have that this is

01:12:36.180 --> 01:12:40.230 align:middle line:90%
converging to the derivative.

01:12:40.230 --> 01:12:44.220 align:middle line:84%
And the only case we have to
look at where this derivative is

01:12:44.220 --> 01:12:48.010 align:middle line:90%
0-- so we are claiming that--

01:12:48.010 --> 01:12:50.580 align:middle line:84%
so the only case we
are left with that we

01:12:50.580 --> 01:12:57.640 align:middle line:84%
haven't dealt with is, first
of all, where the derivative--

01:12:57.640 --> 01:12:58.790 align:middle line:90%
so let's see.

01:12:58.790 --> 01:13:03.910 align:middle line:84%
So let me just write
down here clearly.

01:13:03.910 --> 01:13:14.295 align:middle line:84%
The remaining case
for the chain rule--

01:13:14.295 --> 01:13:20.620 align:middle line:90%


01:13:20.620 --> 01:13:25.525 align:middle line:84%
so the many cases that
the derivative at x0 is 0.

01:13:25.525 --> 01:13:29.680 align:middle line:90%


01:13:29.680 --> 01:13:33.490 align:middle line:84%
And we have already observed
that if the derivative is

01:13:33.490 --> 01:13:42.140 align:middle line:90%
0 but y is not equal to y0--

01:13:42.140 --> 01:13:46.870 align:middle line:84%
if this is the case,
then actually g

01:13:46.870 --> 01:13:55.370 align:middle line:90%
of f of x minus g of f of x0--

01:13:55.370 --> 01:13:59.660 align:middle line:90%
this thing here still converged.

01:13:59.660 --> 01:14:03.860 align:middle line:84%
In this case here,
where this is the case,

01:14:03.860 --> 01:14:06.990 align:middle line:90%
this has still converged to 0.

01:14:06.990 --> 01:14:12.480 align:middle line:84%
So we still have the
chain rule in that case

01:14:12.480 --> 01:14:14.460 align:middle line:90%
if this here was not the case.

01:14:14.460 --> 01:14:16.520 align:middle line:84%
The only thing we
have to worry about

01:14:16.520 --> 01:14:19.980 align:middle line:90%
is what if y was equal to y0?

01:14:19.980 --> 01:14:24.500 align:middle line:84%
But if y was equal to y0, when
we're looking at the difference

01:14:24.500 --> 01:14:25.500 align:middle line:90%
quotient.

01:14:25.500 --> 01:14:27.930 align:middle line:84%
This is the difference
quotient, after all.

01:14:27.930 --> 01:14:31.770 align:middle line:84%
And so in that case,
this thing here is y0.

01:14:31.770 --> 01:14:33.030 align:middle line:90%
This is y0.

01:14:33.030 --> 01:14:35.870 align:middle line:84%
But in that case, the
difference quotient

01:14:35.870 --> 01:14:37.860 align:middle line:90%
is actually zero already.

01:14:37.860 --> 01:14:42.930 align:middle line:84%
So of course, it's going
to be very close to 0.

01:14:42.930 --> 01:14:44.310 align:middle line:90%
It actually is 0.

01:14:44.310 --> 01:14:49.170 align:middle line:84%
So you see that the remaining
case, that's trivial.

01:14:49.170 --> 01:14:52.020 align:middle line:84%
But we wanted to
first exclude it

01:14:52.020 --> 01:14:55.360 align:middle line:84%
because we wanted to be able
to divide by this difference.

01:14:55.360 --> 01:15:01.410 align:middle line:84%
And then once we have seen
that under that assumption,

01:15:01.410 --> 01:15:04.980 align:middle line:84%
we got the formula we
wanted, then we go back

01:15:04.980 --> 01:15:13.050 align:middle line:84%
and then we say that not only
the remaining issue, first

01:15:13.050 --> 01:15:17.440 align:middle line:84%
of all, was the case where
the derivative was 0,

01:15:17.440 --> 01:15:24.060 align:middle line:84%
but in fact, the only case
that was potentially a problem

01:15:24.060 --> 01:15:26.410 align:middle line:90%
was when y was equal to y0.

01:15:26.410 --> 01:15:29.280 align:middle line:84%
But for that, the
difference quotient

01:15:29.280 --> 01:15:32.260 align:middle line:90%
was actually trivially 0.

01:15:32.260 --> 01:15:34.505 align:middle line:90%
So that's the chain rule.

01:15:34.505 --> 01:15:38.250 align:middle line:90%


01:15:38.250 --> 01:15:41.130 align:middle line:84%
And so we only have
a few minutes left.

01:15:41.130 --> 01:15:45.360 align:middle line:84%
And I won't quite be able to
get through all of the stuff.

01:15:45.360 --> 01:15:47.490 align:middle line:84%
But I can get through
one more lemma.

01:15:47.490 --> 01:15:50.480 align:middle line:90%


01:15:50.480 --> 01:15:54.525 align:middle line:84%
And then I'll pick up
from here next time.

01:15:54.525 --> 01:15:58.960 align:middle line:90%


01:15:58.960 --> 01:16:00.620 align:middle line:90%
The notes are already posted.

01:16:00.620 --> 01:16:06.220 align:middle line:84%
But so the last bit of the
notes we'll do next time.

01:16:06.220 --> 01:16:10.810 align:middle line:90%
So the following lemma here--

01:16:10.810 --> 01:16:18.100 align:middle line:84%
so if you have a function,
say, from R to R,

01:16:18.100 --> 01:16:31.900 align:middle line:84%
and you have that x0
is a local max or min--

01:16:31.900 --> 01:16:37.850 align:middle line:84%
so f is a function from R
to R that is differentiable.

01:16:37.850 --> 01:16:44.540 align:middle line:90%


01:16:44.540 --> 01:16:57.950 align:middle line:84%
And x0 is a local max
or local min for f,

01:16:57.950 --> 01:17:08.300 align:middle line:84%
then the derivative
at x0 is equal to 0.

01:17:08.300 --> 01:17:12.080 align:middle line:84%
Let me remind you what a
local max and local min is.

01:17:12.080 --> 01:17:16.140 align:middle line:90%
So if you take a function--

01:17:16.140 --> 01:17:20.270 align:middle line:84%
so local max, similarly
for local min,

01:17:20.270 --> 01:17:24.140 align:middle line:84%
if you have a function
here, you have here x0,

01:17:24.140 --> 01:17:30.120 align:middle line:84%
a local max means that in a
neighborhood of this point,

01:17:30.120 --> 01:17:34.860 align:middle line:84%
then the value at
x0 is the maximum.

01:17:34.860 --> 01:17:54.340 align:middle line:84%
So local max at x0 means that
there exists delta greater

01:17:54.340 --> 01:18:04.360 align:middle line:84%
than 0 such that if you're
looking at the interval

01:18:04.360 --> 01:18:11.650 align:middle line:84%
to either side of
x0, this interval,

01:18:11.650 --> 01:18:19.900 align:middle line:84%
and you're looking at f here
restricted to this subset,

01:18:19.900 --> 01:18:23.470 align:middle line:90%
then x0 is a local max--

01:18:23.470 --> 01:18:24.320 align:middle line:90%
is a max.

01:18:24.320 --> 01:18:33.040 align:middle line:84%
So this means that f of x0
is equal to the max of f,

01:18:33.040 --> 01:18:43.795 align:middle line:84%
where x here is in this little
interval here, like that.

01:18:43.795 --> 01:18:49.770 align:middle line:90%


01:18:49.770 --> 01:18:54.920 align:middle line:84%
So the idea is that the
function may look like this.

01:18:54.920 --> 01:18:57.510 align:middle line:90%
And this here is x0.

01:18:57.510 --> 01:19:01.050 align:middle line:84%
So you see that in a
neighborhood like this.

01:19:01.050 --> 01:19:05.130 align:middle line:84%
It looks like that you have
that this x0 is a maximum.

01:19:05.130 --> 01:19:07.190 align:middle line:84%
But that might even
be somewhere else,

01:19:07.190 --> 01:19:09.890 align:middle line:90%
where the value is much higher.

01:19:09.890 --> 01:19:15.360 align:middle line:84%
So that's a local maximum, and
similarly for a local minimum.

01:19:15.360 --> 01:19:18.630 align:middle line:84%
And so I won't be able to
actually prove this lemma.

01:19:18.630 --> 01:19:22.130 align:middle line:90%
We will prove that next time.

01:19:22.130 --> 01:19:24.260 align:middle line:84%
And then once we
have that lemma,

01:19:24.260 --> 01:19:26.660 align:middle line:84%
we'll prove what's
called Rolle's theorem.

01:19:26.660 --> 01:19:29.970 align:middle line:84%
And then we will use it to
prove the mean value theorem.

01:19:29.970 --> 01:19:32.700 align:middle line:90%
But I'll do that next time.

01:19:32.700 --> 01:19:37.225 align:middle line:84%
But it's actually in the
notes that I posted already.

01:19:37.225 --> 01:19:40.000 align:middle line:90%